---
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import BlogCard from "../components/BlogCard.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

import { Icon } from "astro-icon/components";
---

<BaseLayout>
        <main class="mainContainer">
          <Header class="header"></Header>

          <section class="blogCardContainer">
            <BlogCard
              class="container"
              title="OAuth Sucks"
              url="blogs/oauth-sucks"
              urlAria="navigate to the OAuth Sucks article"
              releaseDate="February 17th, 2026"
            >
              <p>
                OAuth is the biggest pile of crap and any security benefits that there might be are vastly out-matched by the constant annoyance that is using it.
              </p>
              <p>
                What I love in my life is whenever I try and log into a website, I have to play this game where I have to figure out, "which OAuth provider did I create an account with?"
              </p>
            </BlogCard>

            <BlogCard
              class="container"
              title="Responsibility and Agency - How to build great internal processes"
              url="blogs/great-internal-processes"
              urlAria="navigate to the Responsibility and Agency - How to build great internal processes article"
              releaseDate="Febuary 5th, 2026"
            >
              <p>
                At any company, you'll end up having to have jobs that "keep the lights on". This is common and to be expected. Much the same as when you own a home, someone's gotta do the dishes.
              </p>
                <p>
                    There is a common dysfunction that occurs in companies though, which doesn't usually happen at home. People end up getting an ever-growing set of responsibilities, without an equivalently growing agency to do them.
                </p>
            </BlogCard>

            <BlogCard
              class="container"
              title="Importing a database via a .bacpac file on MacOS"
              url="blogs/bacpac-via-sqlpackage"
              urlAria="navigate to the Importing a database via a .bacpac file on MacOS article"
              releaseDate="December 23, 2025"
            >
              <p>
                As a .NET developer working on MacOS, you'll likely run into a situation 
                where you're trying to use a backed up version of your SQLServer database 
                and do some testing. But, you'll find that the current release of VSCode's 
                MSSQL package doesn't support .bacpac imports right now.
              </p>
            </BlogCard>

            <BlogCard
              class="container"
              title="Advanced Deck-building Guide: Fast Brewing"
              url="blogs/fast-brew"
              urlAria="navigate to the Advanced Deck-building: Fast Brew article"
              releaseDate="December 29, 2024"
            >
              <p>
                Have you ever had a moment where you find a commander and you think
                it's cool but you're not sure if there will be enough cards available
                to make the deck run smoothly, or you weren't sure if it will feel
                good to play so you've not wanted to waste time brewing up a 100-card
                deck? Well, in this guide, I'm going to show you how you can
                dramatically reduce the time it takes to test out a deck idea or even
                just a commander.
              </p>
            </BlogCard>

            <BlogCard
              class="container"
              url="blogs/first-commander-deck"
              title="Build your first Magic: The Gathering - Commander deck"
              urlAria="navigate to the Build your first commander deck article"
              releaseDate="September 29, 2024"
            >
              <p>
                Building your first Commander deck can be both exciting and overwhelming.
                With thousands of cards to choose from and countless strategies to explore,
                it's easy to feel lost. This guide is designed to help new players step
                into the world of Commander. We'll start by commanders that are perfect
                for beginners. Then, we'll walk you through a simple framework for building
                your first deck. Finally, we'll give you a few extra tools to help you
                refine your deck as you play and make it your own!
              </p>
            </BlogCard>

            <BlogCard
              class="container"
              title="Learning Rust"
              url="blogs/rust-game"
              urlAria="navigate to Learning Rust blog post"
              releaseDate="December 10, 2023"
            >
              <p>
                Starting out in the industry there's been one thing I've heard continually:
                Rust is cool, and you should learn it. So, after endless nagging by a few colleagues
                and the swathes of social media that pushes it, I've made the plungeâ€¦
              </p>
            </BlogCard>
          </section>

          <footer class="container footer">
            <ul class="socialsList">
              <li>
                <a href="https://github.com/SamBWagner" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="GitHub profile" aria-label="GitHub profile">
                  <Icon name="simple-line-icons:social-github" class="gitHub" />
                </a>
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/sam-b-wagner" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="LinkedIn profile" aria-label="LinkedIn profile">
                  <Icon name="simple-line-icons:social-linkedin" class="linkedIn" />
                </a>
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="https://www.ssw.com.au/people/sam-wagner/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="SSW People Profile" aria-label="SSW People Profile">
                  <Icon name="simple-line-icons:people" class="ssw-people" />
                </a>
              </li>
              <li>
                <a href="/rss.xml" target="_blank" title="RSS feed" aria-label="RSS feed">
                  <Icon name="simple-line-icons:feed" class="rss" />
                </a>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </footer>
        </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
        .mainContainer {
            align-items: center;
            text-align: center;
            margin-top: auto;
            margin-bottom:auto;
        }

        .header {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            gap: 1rem;

            margin-bottom: 5rem;
            margin-top: 5rem;
        }

        .header h1 {
            margin-top: 0;
            margin-bottom: 0;
        }

        .header h2 {
            margin-top: 0;
            margin-bottom: 0;
        }

        /* .byLineContainer {
        } */

        .byLine {
            font-weight: 600;
            font-size: 2.5rem;
            margin-bottom: 0;
        }

        @media (max-width: 505px) {
            .byLine {
                font-size: 2rem;
            }
        }

        .byLine::before {
            content: " ";
            display: block;
            width: auto;
            border-bottom: 3px solid var(--accent2);
        }

        .footer {
            padding-top: 2rem;
            padding-bottom: 1rem;
            padding-left: 1rem;
            padding-right: 1rem;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            z-index: 100;
            max-width: var(--max-width);
            border-top-left-radius: var(--border-radius);
            border-top-right-radius: var(--border-radius);
        }

        .homeLink {
            font-size: 1.5rem;
            font-family: var(--neuton), 'sans-serif';
            font-weight: 700;
            letter-spacing: 1.5px;
            color: #f4963e;
            text-decoration: none;
            transition: transform 0.2s ease-in-out;
        }

        .homeLink:hover {
            transform: scale(1.1);
            transition: fill 0.2s ease-in-out, transform 0.2s ease;
        }

        .socialsList {
            display: flex;
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
            gap: 2rem;
        }

        .blogCardContainer {
            padding-bottom: 5rem;
            padding-top:5rem;
            padding-right:1rem;
            padding-left:1rem;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            gap: 3rem;
            justify-content: center;
        }

        .blogContainerHeading {
            margin-top: 0;
            margin-bottom: 0;
        }

        .gitHub, .linkedIn, .rss, .ssw-people {
            font-size: 2rem;
            color: var(--accent1);
            transition: fill 0.3s ease, transform 0.3s ease;
        }

        .gitHub:hover, .linkedIn:hover, .rss:hover, .ssw-people:hover {
            cursor: pointer;
            color: var(--accent1-link-hover);
            transform: scale(1.2);
        }
</style>
